{"title_page": "Tekkad\u0131n ruins", "text_new": "[[File:Tekkad\u0131n ruins.jpg|thumb|Tekkad\u0131n ruins (castle)]]\n'''Tekkad\u0131n ruins''' are a group of ruins in [[Mersin Province]], [[Turkey]]. The name of the ruins is a local name meaning \"single woman\". The original name is not known. The ruins are in the rural area of [[Silifke]] [[il\u00e7e]] (district) of Mersin Province at {{coord|36|29|19|N|34|00|27|E}}. The visitors follow Turkish state highway {{jct|country=TUR|D|400 }} and turn north in [[Atakent, Silifke|Atakent]] town. The ruins are about {{convert|11|km}} to Atakent. Distance to Silifke is {{convert|27|km}} and to [[Mersin]] is {{convert|77|km}}.\n\nThe ancient town was a Helenistic town . But it continued during the Roman and early Byzantine times. Presently there is small castle as well as the ruins of a  church, a number of houses, cisterns,rock tombs and sarcophagus lids.<ref name=MV>Mersin \u00d6ren Yerleri, Mersin Valili\u011fi, \u0130stanbul, 2009, {{ISBN|978 605 4196 07 4}} p.219</ref>  \n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mersin Province}}\n{{Castles in Turkey}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in Turkey]]\n[[Category:History of Mersin Province]]\n[[Category:Silifke District]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Tekkad\u0131n ruins.jpg|thumb|Tekkad\u0131n ruins (castle)]]\n'''Tekkad\u0131n ruins''' are a group of ruins in [[Mersin Province]], [[Turkey]]. The name of the ruins is a local name meaning \"single woman\". The original name is not known. The ruins are in the rural area of [[Silifke]] [[il\u00e7e]] (district) of Mersin Province at {{coord|36|29|19|N|34|00|27|E}}. The visitors follow Turkish state highway {{jct|country=TUR|D|400 }} and turn north in [[Atakent, Silifke|Atakent]] town. The ruins are about {{convert|11|km}} to Atakent. Distance to Silifke is {{convert|27|km}} and to [[Mersin]] is {{convert|77|km}}. \n\nThe ancient town was a Helenistic town . But it continued during the Roman and early Byzantine times. Presently there is small castle as well as the ruins of a  church , a number of houses, cisterns,rock tombs and sarcophagus lids. <ref name=MV>Mersin \u00d6ren Yerleri, Mersin Valili\u011fi, \u0130stanbul, 2009, {{ISBN|978 605 4196 07 4}} p.219</ref>  \n \n==Reference==\n{{reference}}\n\n{{Mersin Province}}\n{{Castles in Turkey}}\n\n\n[[Category:Castles in Turkey]]\n[[Category:History of Mersin Province]]\n[[Category:Silifke District]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tekkad%C4%B1n_ruins"}
{"title_page": "Hay Dale", "text_new": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Hay Dale|map_alt=|photo=Hay Dale on Limestone Way.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=Hay Dale on the Limestone Way|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2902|-1.8207|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|elevation_ref=|direction=North-South|length={{Convert|0.75|mi|0}}|width={{Convert|120|m|0}}|area=|depth={{Convert|30|m|0}}|type=|elevation_m=|boundaries=|topo=|towns=|traversed=|watercourses=|footnotes=|embed=}}\n[[File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|thumb|Northern End of Hay Dale]]\n'''Hay Dale''' is a short dry valley near [[Buxton]], [[Derbyshire]], in the [[Peak District]] of England. The foot of the valley leads into Peter Dale to the south and on into [[Monk's Dale]].<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nHay Dale is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]]. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] ([[Lathkill Dale]], [[Cressbrook Dale]], Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale]]). The [[Carboniferous Limestone|Carboniferous limestone]] rocks of the reserve were formed 350 million years ago from the shells and sediments of a tropical sea. The landscape was then sculpted by the ice sheets from the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] 20,000 years ago. The reserve contains ash woodland, limestone grassland and many wildflowers including [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]], [[Primula veris|cowslip]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock rose]] and [[Thymelaeaceae|thyme]]. Butterfies are abundant and include the [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]].<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Limestone Way]] long-distance footpath runs along the length of the gentle valley floor. The [[Pennine Bridleway]] crosses the northern end of the dale. Where the Limestone Way crosses the A623 road (about 1&nbsp;km north of Hay Dale), the route of the old [[Batham Gate]] [[Roman roads|Roman road]] runs east\u2013west.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nAccess into Haydale from the South can be made from the village of Wormhill along the Pennine Bridleway and through Peter Dale. From the North there is a footpath from the village on Peak Forest (on the A623 road) through Dam Dale.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Hay Dale|map_alt=|photo=Hay Dale on Limestone Way.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=Hay Dale on the Limestone Way|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2902|-1.8207|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|elevation_ref=|direction=North-South|length={{Convert|0.75|mi|0}}|width={{Convert|120|m|0}}|area=|depth={{Convert|30|m|0}}|type=|elevation_m=|boundaries=|topo=|towns=|traversed=|watercourses=|footnotes=|embed=}}\n[[File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hay_Dale,northern_end_-_geograph.org.uk_-_62084.jpg|thumb|Northern End of Hay Dale]]\n'''Hay Dale''' is a short dry valley near [[Buxton]], [[Derbyshire]], in the [[Peak District]] of England. The foot of the valley leads into Peter Dale to the south and on into [[Monk's Dale]].<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nHay Dale is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]]. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] ([[Lathkill Dale]], [[Cressbrook Dale]], Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale]]). The [[Carboniferous Limestone|Carboniferous limestone]] rocks of the reserve were formed 350 million years ago from the shells and sediments of a tropical sea. The landscape was then scuplted by the ice sheets from the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] 20,000 years ago. The reserve contains ash woodland, limestone grassland and many wildflowers including [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]], [[Primula veris|cowslip]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock rose]] and [[Thymelaeaceae|thyme]]. Butterfies are abundant and include the [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]].<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Limestone Way]] long-distance footpath runs along the length of the gentle valley floor. The [[Pennine Bridleway]] crosses the northern end of the dale. Where the Limestone Way crosses the A623 road (about 1km north of Hay Dale), the route of the old [[Batham Gate]] [[Roman roads|Roman road]] runs east-west.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nAccess into Haydale from the South can be made from the village of Wormhill along the Pennine Bridleway and through Peter Dale. From the North there is a footpath from the village on Peak Forest (on the A623 road) through Dam Dale.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: east-west \u2192 east\u2013west, scuplted \u2192 sculpted", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hay_Dale"}
{"title_page": "Black and White Lodges", "text_new": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name        = Black and White Lodges\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = [[Dale Cooper]], [[The Man from Another Place]], seated center, [[Laura Palmer]] in the Red Room.\n| source      = [[Twin Peaks]]\n| country     = \n| creator     = [[David Lynch]], [[Mark Frost]]\n| ruler       = \n| genre       = [[Drama]]\n| type        = [[Parallel universe (fiction)|Alternate dimension]]\n| locations   = \n| people      = \n| population  = \n| first       = \n| last        = \n}}\n\nThe '''Black Lodge''' is a fictional setting featured in the [[television series]] ''[[Twin Peaks]]''. It is an [[Parallel universe (fiction)|extradimensional]] place which seems to include, primarily, the \"Red Room\" first seen by [[Dale Cooper|Agent Cooper]] in a dream early in the series. As events in the series unfold, it becomes apparent that the characters from the Red Room, the room itself and the Black Lodge, along with the '''White Lodge''', are connected.\n\n==History==\nAt first it is revealed that there is a mysterious dark presence in the woods that the town's Bookhouse Boys have been combatting for generations. Although they do not know what it is, [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] policeman [[Deputy Hawk]] says that the Black Lodge is from the mythology of his people, describing it as:\n<blockquote>\nThe shadow-self of the White Lodge. The legend says that every spirit must pass through there on the way to perfection. There, you will meet your own shadow self. My people call it 'The [[Guardian of the Threshold|Dweller on the Threshold]]' ... But it is said, if you confront the Black Lodge with imperfect courage, it will utterly annihilate your soul.\n</blockquote>\n\nDuring the second season, [[Windom Earle]] relates a story about the White Lodge:\n<blockquote>\nOnce upon a time, there was a place of great goodness, called the White Lodge. Gentle fawns gamboled there amidst happy, laughing spirits. The sounds of innocence and joy filled the air. And when it rained, it rained sweet nectar that infused one's heart with a desire to live life in truth and beauty. Generally speaking, a ghastly place, reeking of virtue's sour smell. Engorged with the whispered prayers of kneeling mothers, mewling newborns, and fools, young and old, compelled to do good without reason ... But, I am happy to point out that our story does not end in this wretched place of saccharine excess. For there's another place, its opposite: A place of almost unimaginable power, chock full of dark forces and vicious secrets. No prayers dare enter this frightful maw. The spirits there care not for good deeds or priestly invocations, they're as likely to rip the flesh from your bone as greet you with a happy \"good day.\" And if harnessed, these spirits in this hidden land of unmuffled screams and broken hearts would offer up a power so vast that its bearer might reorder the Earth itself to his liking.\n</blockquote>\n\nAs the Black and White Lodges become more prominent in the story, [[Major Briggs]] claims that during one or more of his disappearances, he had visited the White Lodge and goes on to offer advice regarding it. There is no clear evidence of him being affected by the Black Lodge and it is not clear how he arrives there - aside from a bright flash of light - or what the purpose of his trips were.\n\n==Location==\nAlthough the Red Room began exclusively as a location within Agent [[Dale Cooper]]'s dreams, the inhabitants began appearing in other locations in the town, inciting other elements in the plot, to the point where the Red Room and White/Black Lodge stories became one. After discovering a mysterious map in Owl Cave, it becomes evident to Earle and Cooper\u2014both independently and with different motivations for wanting to visit it\u2014that the entrance to the Black Lodge is located in Ghostwood Forest which surrounds the town of Twin Peaks, at a pool of a substance that smells like scorched [[engine oil]] and surrounded by 12 young [[Platanus|sycamore trees]]. This area is known as Glastonbury Grove.\n\nIt is said that the key to gain entrance to the Black Lodge is fear\u2014usually an act of brutal murder. This is in contrast to the key to the White Lodge, which is love. Another requirement to enter the Black Lodge through the entrance in Glastonbury Grove is that it may only be entered \"...when [[Jupiter]] and [[Saturn]] meet...\" When the above requirements are met and one approaches the pool in Glastonbury Grove, red curtains appear, which the person walks between before the curtains vanish once again.\n\n==Interior==\nThere is little furniture in the Red Room aside from a few armchairs, a wheeled table and a couple of floor lamps. There is also a statue of the [[Venus de Medici]], easily mistaken for the [[Venus de Milo]] (the Venus de Milo can be seen in the hallway). There are no doors to speak of; movement from room to room is accomplished by crossing through another set of red curtains that lead to a narrow hallway. The floor is a chevron pattern of brown and white, and all sides of any room and all walls of any hallway encountered are covered by identical red curtains. In the final episode, a second room in the Lodge is seen, identical to the first. Between the two rooms is a narrow corridor which has the same floor and \"walls\" as the other two rooms.\n\nAlthough the Lodge inhabitants speak English, their voices are warped and strangely clipped and their movements are unnatural (this effect is accomplished by the actors performing in reverse and the footage is then played backwards). Residents often speak in riddles and [[Non sequitur (literary device)|non-sequitur]]s. The main inhabitants of the Lodge are [[The Man from Another Place]], [[The Giant (Twin Peaks)|The Giant]] and [[Killer Bob]].\n\nIn the final episode of ''Twin Peaks'', Cooper meets The Man from Another Place, who refers to the Red Room as the \"waiting room\". This coincides with Hawk's claim that every spirit must pass through the Black Lodge on the way to perfection and that the Red Room leads to the White Lodge as well.\n\nThe red curtains, zig-zag floors and bright spotlights of the White and Black Lodges have also appeared in several of [[David Lynch]]'s other films, suggesting that Lynch may view their influences as ongoing in his narrative worlds.<ref name=\"decoded\">{{cite book |last=Stewart |first=Mark Allyn |title=''David Lynch Decoded'' |publisher=AuthorHouse |year=2007 |pages=113 |isbn=1-4343-4985-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BGeXiWl-DQcC&pg=PA55&dq=%22log+lady%22&lr=#PPA56,M1 |accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref> As the [[Masonic]] historian archeologist [[David Harrison (historian)|Dr. David Harrison]] notes in his article on ''Twin Peaks'', the floor resembles a zig-zag version of the ''Mosaic Pavement'' in a [[Masonic lodge]], hence the names ''Black Lodge'' and ''White Lodge'', which consists of squares in the middle, but of triangles at the borders. As the focus of the series is on how to pass through from one surreal realm into the other, or how to transcend from one level of fear of this metaphysical realm to the one associated with love and that both are a way to come to a cumulative, final interpretation on the matter of [[reality]] itself, reachable from ''both sides of the medal'', the condensation and reduction of the symbolism to a zig-zag floor makes sense in context of the series' themes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. David Harrison: ''Twin Peaks and its Occult Themes''|url=https://dr-david-harrison.com/|publisher=Dr. David Harrison|date=July 24, 2017| accessdate= January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Inhabitants==\nThe Black Lodge and White Lodges are home to many spirits and people alike including BOB, [[Mike (Twin Peaks)|MIKE]], [[The Man From Another Place]], [[The Giant (Twin Peaks)|The Giant]], [[Laura Palmer]] (passing through the Red Room before ascending to the White Lodge), [[Chester Desmond]], [[Phillip Jeffries]], and Dale Cooper.\n\nThe spirits can possess humans if they are let in: BOB possessed [[Leland Palmer]], but not Laura, who wouldn't let him in. Later BOB possessed Dale Cooper's doppelganger (not Cooper himself); The Giant and an elderly waiter from the Great Northern Hotel were \"one and the same\". MIKE and The Man From Another Place (MIKE's arm) possessed Phillip Gerard.\n\n==References in popular culture==\n\nIn the two-part ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode, \"[[Who Shot Mr. Burns?]],\" [[Chief Wiggum|Chief Clancy Wiggum]] has trouble solving the case and falls into a dream sequence in which he sits in the Red Room with [[Lisa Simpson]], who speaks backwards. She gives him clues in reverse-speak, but Wiggum is unable to understand her until she gives up in frustration and speaks normally.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book |last=Groening |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Groening |editor1-first=Ray |editor1-last=Richmond |editor1-link=Ray Richmond |editor2-first=Antonia |editor2-last=Coffman |title=[[The Simpsons episode guides#The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family|The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family]] |edition=1st |year=1997 |location=New York |publisher=[[HarperPerennial]] |lccn=98141857 |ol=433519M |oclc=37796735 |isbn=978-0-06-095252-5 |ref={{harvid|Richmond & Coffman|1997}} |pages=[https://archive.org/details/simpsonscomplete00groe/page/176 176\u2013177; 180\u2013181] }}</ref> As with ''Twin Peaks'', while recording Lisa's lines for the segment, [[Yeardley Smith]] recorded the part backwards and it was reversed.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season6/page25.shtml |title=Who Shot Mr. Burns? (Part One) |accessdate=2007-05-07 |author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |year=2000 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref name=\"Mirkin2\">{{cite video |people=Mirkin, David |date=2005 |title=Commentary for the episode \"Who Shot Mr. Burns (Part Two)\". The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Several other parts in the segment are direct references to ''Twin Peaks'', including a moving shadow on the curtain, and Wiggum's hair standing straight up after waking.<ref name=\"Oakley2\">{{cite video |people=Oakley, Bill |date=2005 |title=Commentary for the episode \"Who Shot Mr. Burns (Part Two)\". The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nIn the manga series ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]'', the Red Room is used as a motif when [[List of Soul Eater characters#Soul Eater Evans|Soul Eater]] and [[Maka Albarn]] are infected with Black Blood. A demon who dances backward (similar to [[The Man from Another Place]]) to a skipping jazz record attempts to convince them to give in to the Black Blood's madness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aminoapps.com/c/anime/page/blog/twin-peaks-reference-in-soul-eater/70tP_u8jwZnrmBkKo2EZYw1xVJZoYk|title=Twin Peaks reference in Soul Eater|last=Roricon|first=|date=2016-01-02|website=aminoapps.com|access-date=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Red Room is also parodied as \"The Sitting Room\" in multiple episodes of ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]],'' first accessed by Scooby-Doo in a dream and later accessed by all of Mystery, Inc. under mass hypnosis. A helper figure similar to The Man from Another Place appears there, and, like the original Man, is played by [[Michael J. Anderson]]. The Sitting Room appears to be a spirit realm where both helpful and malicious entities can dwell, as well as pieces of the souls of those tainted by the Treasure of Crystal Cove.<ref name=\"MarySue\">{{cite web |url=http://www.themarysue.com/scooby-doo-twin-peaks/ |title=Remember That Time Scooby-Doo Crossed Over With Twin Peaks? [VIDEO] |accessdate=2017-03-16 |author1=Pahle, Rebecca |year=2013 |publisher=The Mary Sue}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, [[Atlus]] co-founder [[Kazuma Kaneko]] confirmed that the Black Lodge was the main source of inspiration for the Velvet Room's design in the ''[[Persona (series)|Persona]]'' video game series, though the color of the room was altered to blue in reference to [[David Lynch]]'s film ''[[Blue Velvet (film)|Blue Velvet]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://anitay.kinja.com/the-influences-of-persona-part-2-twin-peaks-1794974335|title=The Influences of Persona - Part 2: Twin Peaks|last=The Gespenst|date=2017-06-14|work=AniTAY|access-date=2018-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817224502/http://anitay.kinja.com/the-influences-of-persona-part-2-twin-peaks-1794974335|archive-date=2017-08-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe cult classic video game ''[[Deadly Premonition]]'', that was heavily influenced by Twin Peaks, also has a Red Room of sorts that the protagonist Agent York Morgan visits on his dreams.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Green|first1=Holly|title=The 7 Most Striking Similarities Between Twin Peaks and Deadly Premonition|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/05/the-7-most-striking-similarities-between-twin-peak.html|website=Paste Magazine|accessdate=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe video game ''[[The Evil Within 2]]'' frequently uses the Red Room motif, in association with one of the primary antagonists, Stefano Valentini.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iwaniuk|first1=Phil|title=The Evil Within 2 review-in-progress|url=http://www.trustedreviews.com/reviews/evil-within-2|website=Trusted Reviews|publisher=Time|accessdate=October 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn an episode of ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' in September 2017, the opening segment featured actor [[Kyle MacLachlan]] having turned his dressing room into the Red Room, including speaking in the warped backwards manner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=See Kyle MacLachlan, Judi Dench's 'Twin Peaks' Spoof on 'Corden'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/see-kyle-maclachlan-judi-denchs-twin-peaks-spoof-w504857|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt is also referenced in ''[[All Hail King Julien]]'' in the third episode of season three \"Dance, Dance, Resolution\" in which Mort speaks backwards to King Julien in the black lodge, you can see the mythical pineapple shadow on the red curtains and King Julien's parents there, to which King Julian asks \"Mort why are you talking backwards!?\", Mort then does a strange forward walk that also seems somewhat backwards to which King Julien's parents clap, King Julien then tries to please his parents which then turns into Maurice, then King Julien awakes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://welcometotwinpeaks.com/references/all-hail-king-julien-twin-peaks/|title=Dreamworks Pays Homage To Twin Peaks In New \"All Hail King Julien\" Season|last=Dom|first=Pieter|date=June 17, 2016|website=Welcome to Twin Peaks|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==\"Black Lodge\" (song)==\n''Twin Peaks''' [[Film score|score]] conductor [[Angelo Badalamenti]] helped write the song \"Black Lodge\" on the [[1993 in music|1993]] ''[[Sound of White Noise]]'' album by [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Soundtrack from Twin Peaks|last=Norelli|first=Clare Nina|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Academic]]|year=2017|isbn=9781501323010|series=[[33 1/3]]|location=New York|pages=119}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Twin Peaks}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional dimensions]]\n[[Category:Twin Peaks locations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name        = Black and White Lodges\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = [[Dale Cooper]], [[The Man from Another Place]], seated center, [[Laura Palmer]] in the Red Room.\n| source      = [[Twin Peaks]]\n| country     = \n| creator     = [[David Lynch]], [[Mark Frost]]\n| ruler       = \n| genre       = [[Drama]]\n| type        = [[Parallel universe (fiction)|Alternate dimension]]\n| locations   = \n| people      = \n| population  = \n| first       = \n| last        = \n}}\n\nThe '''Black Lodge''' is a fictional setting featured in the [[television series]] ''[[Twin Peaks]]''. It is an [[Parallel universe (fiction)|extradimensional]] place which seems to include, primarily, the \"Red Room\" first seen by [[Dale Cooper|Agent Cooper]] in a dream early in the series. As events in the series unfold, it becomes apparent that the characters from the Red Room, the room itself and the Black Lodge, along with the '''White Lodge''', are connected.\n\n==History==\nAt first it is revealed that there is a mysterious dark presence in the woods that the town's Bookhouse Boys have been combatting for generations. Although they do not know what it is, [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] policeman [[Deputy Hawk]] says that the Black Lodge is from the mythology of his people, describing it as:\n<blockquote>\nThe shadow-self of the White Lodge. The legend says that every spirit must pass through there on the way to perfection. There, you will meet your own shadow self. My people call it 'The [[Guardian of the Threshold|Dweller on the Threshold]]' ... But it is said, if you confront the Black Lodge with imperfect courage, it will utterly annihilate your soul.\n</blockquote>\n\nDuring the second season, [[Windom Earle]] relates a story about the White Lodge:\n<blockquote>\nOnce upon a time, there was a place of great goodness, called the White Lodge. Gentle fawns gamboled there amidst happy, laughing spirits. The sounds of innocence and joy filled the air. And when it rained, it rained sweet nectar that infused one's heart with a desire to live life in truth and beauty. Generally speaking, a ghastly place, reeking of virtue's sour smell. Engorged with the whispered prayers of kneeling mothers, mewling newborns, and fools, young and old, compelled to do good without reason ... But, I am happy to point out that our story does not end in this wretched place of saccharine excess. For there's another place, its opposite: A place of almost unimaginable power, chock full of dark forces and vicious secrets. No prayers dare enter this frightful maw. The spirits there care not for good deeds or priestly invocations, they're as likely to rip the flesh from your bone as greet you with a happy \"good day.\" And if harnessed, these spirits in this hidden land of unmuffled screams and broken hearts would offer up a power so vast that its bearer might reorder the Earth itself to his liking.\n</blockquote>\n\nAs the Black and White Lodges become more prominent in the story, [[Major Briggs]] claims that during one or more of his disappearances, he had visited the White Lodge and goes on to offer advice regarding it. There is no clear evidence of him being affected by the Black Lodge and it is not clear how he arrives there - aside from a bright flash of light - or what the purpose of his trips was.\n\n==Location==\nAlthough the Red Room began exclusively as a location within Agent [[Dale Cooper]]'s dreams, the inhabitants began appearing in other locations in the town, inciting other elements in the plot, to the point where the Red Room and White/Black Lodge stories became one. After discovering a mysterious map in Owl Cave, it becomes evident to Earle and Cooper\u2014both independently and with different motivations for wanting to visit it\u2014that the entrance to the Black Lodge is located in Ghostwood Forest which surrounds the town of Twin Peaks, at a pool of a substance that smells like scorched [[engine oil]] and surrounded by 12 young [[Platanus|sycamore trees]]. This area is known as Glastonbury Grove.\n\nIt is said that the key to gain entrance to the Black Lodge is fear\u2014usually an act of brutal murder. This is in contrast to the key to the White Lodge, which is love. Another requirement to enter the Black Lodge through the entrance in Glastonbury Grove is that it may only be entered \"...when [[Jupiter]] and [[Saturn]] meet...\" When the above requirements are met and one approaches the pool in Glastonbury Grove, red curtains appear, which the person walks between before the curtains vanish once again.\n\n==Interior==\nThere is little furniture in the Red Room aside from a few armchairs, a wheeled table and a couple of floor lamps. There is also a statue of the [[Venus de Medici]], easily mistaken for the [[Venus de Milo]] (the Venus de Milo can be seen in the hallway). There are no doors to speak of; movement from room to room is accomplished by crossing through another set of red curtains that lead to a narrow hallway. The floor is a chevron pattern of brown and white, and all sides of any room and all walls of any hallway encountered are covered by identical red curtains. In the final episode, a second room in the Lodge is seen, identical to the first. Between the two rooms is a narrow corridor which has the same floor and \"walls\" as the other two rooms.\n\nAlthough the Lodge inhabitants speak English, their voices are warped and strangely clipped and their movements are unnatural (this effect is accomplished by the actors performing in reverse and the footage is then played backwards). Residents often speak in riddles and [[Non sequitur (literary device)|non-sequitur]]s. The main inhabitants of the Lodge are [[The Man from Another Place]], [[The Giant (Twin Peaks)|The Giant]] and [[Killer Bob]].\n\nIn the final episode of ''Twin Peaks'', Cooper meets The Man from Another Place, who refers to the Red Room as the \"waiting room\". This coincides with Hawk's claim that every spirit must pass through the Black Lodge on the way to perfection and that the Red Room leads to the White Lodge as well.\n\nThe red curtains, zig-zag floors and bright spotlights of the White and Black Lodges have also appeared in several of [[David Lynch]]'s other films, suggesting that Lynch may view their influences as ongoing in his narrative worlds.<ref name=\"decoded\">{{cite book |last=Stewart |first=Mark Allyn |title=''David Lynch Decoded'' |publisher=AuthorHouse |year=2007 |pages=113 |isbn=1-4343-4985-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BGeXiWl-DQcC&pg=PA55&dq=%22log+lady%22&lr=#PPA56,M1 |accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref> As the [[Masonic]] historian archeologist [[David Harrison (historian)|Dr. David Harrison]] notes in his article on ''Twin Peaks'', the floor resembles a zig-zag version of the ''Mosaic Pavement'' in a [[Masonic lodge]], hence the names ''Black Lodge'' and ''White Lodge'', which consists of squares in the middle, but of triangles at the borders. As the focus of the series is on how to pass through from one surreal realm into the other, or how to transcend from one level of fear of this metaphysical realm to the one associated with love and that both are a way to come to a cumulative, final interpretation on the matter of [[reality]] itself, reachable from ''both sides of the medal'', the condensation and reduction of the symbolism to a zig-zag floor makes sense in context of the series' themes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. David Harrison: ''Twin Peaks and its Occult Themes''|url=https://dr-david-harrison.com/|publisher=Dr. David Harrison|date=July 24, 2017| accessdate= January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Inhabitants==\nThe Black Lodge and White Lodges are home to many spirits and people alike including BOB, [[Mike (Twin Peaks)|MIKE]], [[The Man From Another Place]], [[The Giant (Twin Peaks)|The Giant]], [[Laura Palmer]] (passing through the Red Room before ascending to the White Lodge), [[Chester Desmond]], [[Phillip Jeffries]], and Dale Cooper.\n\nThe spirits can possess humans if they are let in: BOB possessed [[Leland Palmer]], but not Laura, who wouldn't let him in. Later BOB possessed Dale Cooper's doppelganger (not Cooper himself); The Giant and an elderly waiter from the Great Northern Hotel were \"one and the same\". MIKE and The Man From Another Place (MIKE's arm) possessed Phillip Gerard.\n\n==References in popular culture==\n\nIn the two-part ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode, \"[[Who Shot Mr. Burns?]],\" [[Chief Wiggum|Chief Clancy Wiggum]] has trouble solving the case and falls into a dream sequence in which he sits in the Red Room with [[Lisa Simpson]], who speaks backwards. She gives him clues in reverse-speak, but Wiggum is unable to understand her until she gives up in frustration and speaks normally.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book |last=Groening |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Groening |editor1-first=Ray |editor1-last=Richmond |editor1-link=Ray Richmond |editor2-first=Antonia |editor2-last=Coffman |title=[[The Simpsons episode guides#The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family|The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family]] |edition=1st |year=1997 |location=New York |publisher=[[HarperPerennial]] |lccn=98141857 |ol=433519M |oclc=37796735 |isbn=978-0-06-095252-5 |ref={{harvid|Richmond & Coffman|1997}} |pages=[https://archive.org/details/simpsonscomplete00groe/page/176 176\u2013177; 180\u2013181] }}</ref> As with ''Twin Peaks'', while recording Lisa's lines for the segment, [[Yeardley Smith]] recorded the part backwards and it was reversed.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season6/page25.shtml |title=Who Shot Mr. Burns? (Part One) |accessdate=2007-05-07 |author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |year=2000 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref name=\"Mirkin2\">{{cite video |people=Mirkin, David |date=2005 |title=Commentary for the episode \"Who Shot Mr. Burns (Part Two)\". The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Several other parts in the segment are direct references to ''Twin Peaks'', including a moving shadow on the curtain, and Wiggum's hair standing straight up after waking.<ref name=\"Oakley2\">{{cite video |people=Oakley, Bill |date=2005 |title=Commentary for the episode \"Who Shot Mr. Burns (Part Two)\". The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nIn the manga series ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]'', the Red Room is used as a motif when [[List of Soul Eater characters#Soul Eater Evans|Soul Eater]] and [[Maka Albarn]] are infected with Black Blood. A demon who dances backward (similar to [[The Man from Another Place]]) to a skipping jazz record attempts to convince them to give in to the Black Blood's madness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aminoapps.com/c/anime/page/blog/twin-peaks-reference-in-soul-eater/70tP_u8jwZnrmBkKo2EZYw1xVJZoYk|title=Twin Peaks reference in Soul Eater|last=Roricon|first=|date=2016-01-02|website=aminoapps.com|access-date=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Red Room is also parodied as \"The Sitting Room\" in multiple episodes of ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]],'' first accessed by Scooby-Doo in a dream and later accessed by all of Mystery, Inc. under mass hypnosis. A helper figure similar to The Man from Another Place appears there, and, like the original Man, is played by [[Michael J. Anderson]]. The Sitting Room appears to be a spirit realm where both helpful and malicious entities can dwell, as well as pieces of the souls of those tainted by the Treasure of Crystal Cove.<ref name=\"MarySue\">{{cite web |url=http://www.themarysue.com/scooby-doo-twin-peaks/ |title=Remember That Time Scooby-Doo Crossed Over With Twin Peaks? [VIDEO] |accessdate=2017-03-16 |author1=Pahle, Rebecca |year=2013 |publisher=The Mary Sue}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, [[Atlus]] co-founder [[Kazuma Kaneko]] confirmed that the Black Lodge was the main source of inspiration for the Velvet Room's design in the ''[[Persona (series)|Persona]]'' video game series, though the color of the room was altered to blue in reference to [[David Lynch]]'s film ''[[Blue Velvet (film)|Blue Velvet]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://anitay.kinja.com/the-influences-of-persona-part-2-twin-peaks-1794974335|title=The Influences of Persona - Part 2: Twin Peaks|last=The Gespenst|date=2017-06-14|work=AniTAY|access-date=2018-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817