h then turns into Maurice, then King Julien awakes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://welcometotwinpeaks.com/references/all-hail-king-julien-twin-peaks/|title=Dreamworks Pays Homage To Twin Peaks In New \"All Hail King Julien\" Season|last=Dom|first=Pieter|date=June 17, 2016|website=Welcome to Twin Peaks|accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==\"Black Lodge\" (song)==\n''Twin Peaks''' [[Film score|score]] conductor [[Angelo Badalamenti]] helped write the song \"Black Lodge\" on the [[1993 in music|1993]] ''[[Sound of White Noise]]'' album by [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Soundtrack from Twin Peaks|last=Norelli|first=Clare Nina|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Academic]]|year=2017|isbn=9781501323010|series=[[33 1/3]]|location=New York|pages=119}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Twin Peaks}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional dimensions]]\n[[Category:Twin Peaks locations]]\n", "name_user": "Rhombuth", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:- Grammaer - was > were", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_and_White_Lodges"}
{"title_page": "Philippe Higonet", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Baron Philippe Higonet\n| image         = Philippe Higonet.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1782|05|05}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|1859|02|12|1782|05|05}}\n| birth_place   = in [[Saint-Geniez-d'Olt]] ([[Aveyron]])\n| death_place   = in [[Aurillac]] ([[Cantal]])\n| rank          = [[General officer|Brigadier General]]\n| commands      = [[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis|Spain expedition (1823)]]<br/>[[Morea expedition|Morea expedition (1828)]]\n| battles       = [[File:Napoleonic Eagle.svg|20px]] [[Napoleonic Wars]]\n| awards        = [[Baron]]<br/>[[Order of Saint Louis|''Commander'' of the Order of Saint-Louis]]<br/>[[Lists of L\u00e9gion d'honneur recipients|''Commander'' of the Legion of Honour]]<br/> [[Order of the Redeemer|''Commander'' of the Order of the Redeemer (Greece)]]<br/>[[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand|''Grand officer'' of the Order of Saint Ferdinand (Spain)]]\n| laterwork     = [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] ([[Cantal|district of Cantal]]):\n* [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of the Second Restoration]] (1827\u20131830) \n* [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of the July Monarchy]] (1830)\n| signature     = \n}}\n'''Philippe Higonet''' was a [[French people|French]] [[General officer|General]] and politician. He was born on 5 May 1782 in [[Saint-Geniez-d'Olt]] ([[Aveyron]]) and died on 7 April 1862 in [[Aurillac]] ([[Cantal]]).<ref name=\":13\">{{DicoParlement|id=14695|article=Higonet (Philippe, baron)}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Base L\u00e9onore|LH/1300/58}} .</ref><ref name=\":22\">Bernard Maury, \u00ab ''[http://www.genealogie-aveyron.fr/spip.php?article1295 G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Baron Philippe Higonet, Comment un Marmot est devenu G\u00e9n\u00e9ral et Baron]'' \u00bb, Cercle g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique de l\u2019Aveyron, \u00e9dit\u00e9 par Suzanne Barthe, 27 juillet 2018.</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n\n=== Youth ===\nSon of Joseph Higonet, master [[apothecary]], and of Marie Massabuau, Philippe Higonet was born on Sunday 5 May 1782, in [[Saint-Geniez-d'Olt|Saint-Geniez-d\u2019Olt]], [[Aveyron]]''.'' He was born in a family of nine children and was the younger brother of the future Colonel Joseph Higonet. He left his father's laboratory at the age of 21 to join the military [[camp of Boulogne]], where [[Napoleon]] was assembling his \"[[Grande Arm\u00e9e]]\". He then enlisted, on 20 April 1804, in the 4th Regiment of Line Infantry. He was immediately appointed [[Corporal]], then [[Sergeant]] on 30 June 1804.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Napoleonic Wars ===\nOn 9 February 1805, he was assigned with the rank of [[Lieutenant]] to the 108th Regiment of Line Infantry, which was commanded by Colonel Joseph Higonet, his older brother. He was part of the [[3rd Army Corps (France)|3rd Corps]] of Marshal [[Louis-Nicolas Davout|Marshal Davout]]. On 8 November 1805, he took part in the battle of [[Mariazell]] where his conduct was described as \"''bold and brilliant''\". A few days later, on 2 December 1805, he signaled himself again at the [[Battle of Austerlitz]] where he was wounded in the right thigh.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\nHigonet was named [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] on 4 January 1806 and was knighted in the [[Legion of Honour|Order of the Legion of Honour]] on 14 May 1806.<ref name=\":0\" /> During the [[Battle of Jena\u2013Auerstedt|battle of Auerstedt]] (14 October 1806), captain Higonet showed skill and daring, but his brother, Colonel Joseph Higonet, died there (his name would later be [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|engraved]] [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|under the Arc de Triomphe]], Eastern pillar, column 18). He distinguished himself again on 8 February 1807 during the [[battle of Eylau]], where he was again wounded in the left leg and the lower abdomen. In 1809, he took part in the [[Battle of Eckm\u00fchl|battles of Eckm\u00fchl]] (21-22 April 1809) and [[Battle of Wagram|Wagram]] (5-6 July 1809). His heroic conduct was rewarded on 22 June 1809 by his assignment to the 1st Infantry Grenadier Regiment from the prestigious [[Imperial Guard (Napoleon I)|Imperial Guard]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\nIn 1812 he was still Captain of the Grenadiers of the Imperial Guard when he took part in the [[French invasion of Russia|campaign of Russia]]. He returned with a frozen foot and the rank of [[Major]] in second. During the campaign of Germany, he took part in the siege of [[Hamburg]] in September 1813. On 1 March 1814, just before the abdication of Emperor Napoleon I, Marshal Davout elevated him to the rank of [[Colonel]], considering him as \"''one of the most brilliant officers in the army''.\"<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\nDuring the first Restoration, king [[Louis XVIII of France]] awarded him the cross of Knight of the [[Order of Saint Louis]]. Shortly after, the Colonel received command of the troops of Aveyron. But when Napoleon returned from [[Elba]], Marshal Davout, Minister of War during the [[Hundred Days]], placed Colonel Higonet at the head of the 10th Line Infantry Regiment, then of his former 108th Line Infantry Regiment. He then distinguished himself at the [[battle of Quatre Bras]] (16 June 1815), where he was wounded twice and then at the [[battle of Waterloo]] (18 June 1815), during the debacle of the French army.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Under the Restoration ===\nAfter Napoleon's second abdication, Philippe Higonet rallied to [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis XVIII]], who appointed him to form and command the Legion of Cantal on 19 August 1815. On 8 June 1816, he married Augustine, daughter of Baron Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de Jujeals de Peyrac de Veillan. King Louis XVIII made him [[Baron]] shortly after. He then chose the motto of his coat of arms as \"''Virtus, labor, pietas''\".<ref name=\":22\" /> He was also made Officer of the [[Legion of Honour|Order of the Legion of Honour]] that same year of 1816.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe command of the 9th Line Infantry Regiment was then entrusted to Colonel Philippe Higonet, with whom he participated in 1823 in the [[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis|expedition of Spain]]. On 11 August 1823, he was promoted to [[Mar\u00e9chal de camp]] (Brigadier General) in recognition of his acts of bravery during the siege of [[Pamplona]]. During the siege of [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]] on 3 September 1823, he obtained the capitulation of the city on the 28. The campaign finished, he then returned to France in March 1823. The following year, on 8 June 1824, he was promoted Commander of the [[Legion of Honour|Order of the Legion of Honour]] and raised to the dignity of Grand Officer of the [[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand|Order of Saint Ferdinand of Spain]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n[[File:Entrevue_du_g\u00e9n\u00e9ral_Maison_et_d'Ibrahim_Pacha,_\u00e0_Navarin,_septembre_1828_(d\u00e9tail).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|220x220px|The French military expedition of Morea in 1828 (by Jean-Charles Langlois)]]\nBy the ordinance of 24 July 1828, he was then sent to Greece as a field marshal to participate in the [[Morea expedition|Morea expedition (1828)]], under the orders of [[Nicolas Joseph Maison|Marshal Maison]], during the [[Greek War of Independence]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> At the head of the 2nd brigade of the expeditionary forces, he liberated the city of [[Pylos|Navarino]] (on 7 October 1828) from the Turkish-Egyptian occupation troops of [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] and then took the \"Castle of Morea\" of [[Patras]] (on 30 October 1828).<ref name=\":172\">[[Nicolas-Joseph Maison]] (Lieutenant-g\u00e9n\u00e9ral) : ''d\u00e9p\u00eaches adress\u00e9es au ministre de la Guerre Louis-Victor de Caux, vicomte de Blacquetot,'' octobre 1828, in Jacques Mangeart, Chapitre Suppl\u00e9mentaire des ''[https://books.google.gr/books?id=OixCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Souvenirs de la Mor\u00e9e: recueillis pendant le s\u00e9jour des Fran\u00e7ais dans le Pelopon\u00e8se]'', Igonette, Paris, 1830.</ref> Higonet stayed for a few months in Patras and he established there several health commissions for the freed but suffering Greek population, and even managed, in December 1828, to contain an [[Plague (disease)|outbreak of plague]] which was developing in the mountainous villages of [[Kalavryta]] and Vrachni.<ref name=\":152\">Jacques Mangeart, ''[https://books.google.gr/books?id=OixCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Souvenirs de la Mor\u00e9e: recueillis pendant le s\u00e9jour des Fran\u00e7ais dans le Pelopon\u00e8se]'', Igonette; Paris, 1830.</ref> He finally left the Greek soil after four months of mission in the Peloponnese, on 9 January 1829, after having completely liberated Greece from the occupier.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":172\" /><ref>Site internet \"histoire-en-questions.fr\". Blessures d'un soldat de l'Empire</ref> During this campaign, on 22 February 1829, he was promoted by king [[Charles X of France|Charles X]] Commander of the [[Order of Saint Louis|Royal and Military Order of Saint-Louis]] and then, on his return to France, Commander of the [[Order of the Redeemer]] by the new independent Greek State, in 1830.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Parliamentary activities ===\nShortly before the Morea expedition, on 17 November 1827, as President of the electoral college of [[Cantal]], he had been elected deputy (favorable to [[Charles X of France|Charles X]]) of the 1st arrondissement of this department ([[Aurillac]]) at the [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of Deputies]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> He was re-elected for a second term of deputy on 23 June 1830.<ref>List of the parliamentary terms and biography on the site of the French National Assembly: [http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/sycomore/fiche/(num_dept)/14695 ''Philippe Higonet (1782 - 1859)'']</ref>\n\nBut following the [[July Revolution]], he resigned from his deputy mandate on 12 August 1830, and chose exile from the inside. After the [[French Revolution of 1848]], he came out of his retirement and tried to be re-elected for a mandate of representative of the people at the [[National Assembly (France)|National Legislative Assembly]] of the [[French Second Republic|Second Republic]], but this time without success.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Last years ===\nAfter his resignation from his mandate as deputy on 12 August 1830, Philippe Higonet was placed on availability, retired to Aurillac and devoted himself, during eighteen years, to the administration of the domain of the Ch\u00e2teau de Veyrac, to which he made many improvements,<ref name=\":22\" /> and dealt exclusively with agriculture, becoming president of the Cantal Agriculture Society.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nOn 30 May 1848, he retired as a [[Mar\u00e9chal de camp]] (Brigadier General).\n\nHe supported the candidacy of [[Napoleon III|Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte]] during the presidential election of December 1848, but refused to swear allegiance after his coup of 2 December 1851. He then spent the last years of his life at Aurillac. Because of the wounds he received in February 1807 during the battle of Eylau, which made him suffer cruelly, he died on 12 February 1859 in [[Aurillac]], at the age of 77. He was buried in the town's Massigoux cemetery. On one side of the funerary stele, his name and his honorary distinctions are surrounded by a mandorla (oval almond) on which are inscribed the names of his main battles: [[Mariazell]], Austerlitz, Eylau, Les Quatre Bras, San Sebastian, Pamplona, Navarino and the Castle of Morea.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n== Decorations, military ranks and representative positions ==\n* [[File:French_heraldic_crowns_-_baron_et_pair.svg|60px]] 1st [[Baron|Baron Higonet]] (1816)\n* [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] of the district of Cantal (1827-1830)\n* [[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]] (''G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de brigade'') of the French army.\n* French decorations:\n** [[File:Ordre_Royal_et_Militaire_de_Saint-Louis_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Order of Saint Louis|''Commander'' of the Royal and Military Order of Saint-Louis]] (22 February 1829).\n** [[File:Legion_Honneur_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Knight'' of the Order of the Legion of Honour]] (14 May 1806).\n** [[File:Legion_Honneur_Officier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Officer'']] [[Legion of Honour|of the Legion of Honour]] (1816).\n** [[File:Legion_Honneur_Commandeur_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Commander'']] [[Legion of Honour|of the Legion of Honour]] (8 June 1824).\n* Foreign decorations:\n** [[File:ESP_Laureada_pasador.svg|60px]] [[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand|''Grand officer'' of the Order of Saint Ferdinand (Spain)]] (1823)\n** [[File:GRE_Order_Redeemer_3Class.png|60px]] [[Order of the Redeemer|''Commander'' of the Order of the Redeemer (Greece)]] (1830)\n\n== Annexes ==\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* \u00ab Le g\u00e9n\u00e9ral baron Higonet (Philippe)\u00bb , notice dans Aim\u00e9 de Birague, ''M\u00e9morial universel g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique et biographique'', Institut des archives historiques, Paris, 1851\u20131852.\n* {{DicoParlement}}.\n* Bernard Maury, \u00ab ''[http://www.genealogie-aveyron.fr/spip.php?article1295 G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Baron Philippe Higonet, Comment un Marmot est devenu G\u00e9n\u00e9ral et Baron]'' \u00bb, Cercle g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique de l\u2019Aveyron, \u00e9dit\u00e9 par Suzanne Barthe, 27 juillet 2018.\n\n=== External links ===\n* Resources related to his public life: [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/leonore_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=COTE&VALUE_1=LH/875/60 Base L\u00e9onore] ; [http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/sycomore/fiche.asp?num_dept=14443 Base Sycomore] : \n**{{Base L\u00e9onore|LH/1300/58}} (National Order of the Legion of Honour)\n**[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/sycomore/fiche/(num_dept)/14695 \u00ab List of the parliamentary terms of Philippe Higonet (1782 - 1859) \u00bb, Base Sycomore], [[National Assembly (France)|(French National Assembly)]].\n\n=== Linked articles ===\n* [[Morea expedition]]\n* [[List of members of the Morea expedition (1828-1833)]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Portal|histoire militaire|politique fran\u00e7aise|Cantal\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Higonet, Philippe}}\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Saint Louis]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of the Bourbon Restoration]]\n[[Category:People from Cantal]]\n[[Category:WikiProject Europe articles]]\n[[Category:WikiProject France articles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Baron Philippe Higonet\n| image         = Philippe Higonet.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1782|05|05}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|1859|02|12|1782|05|05}}\n| birth_place   = in [[Saint-Geniez-d'Olt]] ([[Aveyron]])\n| death_place   = in [[Aurillac]] ([[Cantal]])\n| rank          = [[General officer|Brigadier General]]\n| commands      = [[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis|Spain expedition (1823)]]<br/>[[Morea expedition|Morea expedition (1828)]]\n| battles       = [[File:Napoleonic Eagle.svg|20px]] [[Napoleonic Wars]]\n| awards        = [[Baron]]<br/>[[Order of Saint Louis|''Commander'' of the Order of Saint-Louis]]<br/>[[Lists of L\u00e9gion d'honneur recipients|''Commander'' of the Legion of Honour]]<br/> [[Order of the Redeemer|''Commander'' of the Order of the Redeemer (Greece)]]<br/>[[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand|''Grand officer'' of the Order of Saint Ferdinand (Spain)]]\n| laterwork     = [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] ([[Cantal|district of Cantal]]):\n* [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of the Second Restoration]] (1827\u20131830) \n* [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of the July Monarchy]] (1830)\n| signature     = \n}}\n'''Philippe Higonet''' was a [[French people|French]] [[General officer|General]] and politician. He was born on 5 May 1782 in [[Saint-Geniez-d'Olt]] ([[Aveyron]]) and died on 7 April 1862 in [[Aurillac]] ([[Cantal]]).<ref name=\":13\">{{DicoParlement|id=14695|article=Higonet (Philippe, baron)}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Base L\u00e9onore|LH/1300/58}} .</ref><ref name=\":22\">Bernard Maury, \u00ab ''[http://www.genealogie-aveyron.fr/spip.php?article1295 G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Baron Philippe Higonet, Comment un Marmot est devenu G\u00e9n\u00e9ral et Baron]'' \u00bb, Cercle g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique de l\u2019Aveyron, \u00e9dit\u00e9 par Suzanne Barthe, 27 juillet 2018.</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n\n=== Youth ===\nSon of Joseph Higonet, master [[apothecary]], and of Marie Massabuau, Philippe Higonet was born on Sunday 5 May 1782, in [[Saint-Geniez-d'Olt|Saint-Geniez-d\u2019Olt]], [[Aveyron]]''.'' He was born in a family of nine children and was the younger brother of the future Colonel Joseph Higonet. He left his father's laboratory at the age of 21 to join the military [[camp of Boulogne]], where [[Napoleon]] was assembling his \"[[Grande Arm\u00e9e]]\". He then enlisted, on 20 April 1804, in the 4th Regiment of Line Infantry. He was immediately appointed [[Corporal]], then [[Sergeant]] on 30 June 1804.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Napoleonic Wars ===\nOn 9 February 1805, he was assigned with the rank of [[Lieutenant]] to the 108th Regiment of Line Infantry, which was commanded by Colonel Joseph Higonet, his older brother. He was part of the [[3rd Army Corps (France)|3rd Corps]] of Marshal [[Louis-Nicolas Davout|Marshal Davout]]. On 8 November 1805, he took part in the battle of [[Mariazell]] where his conduct was described as \"''bold and brilliant''\". A few days later, on 2 December 1805, he signaled himself again at the [[Battle of Austerlitz]] where he was wounded in the right thigh.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\nHigonet was named [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] on 4 January 1806 and was knighted in the [[Legion of Honour|Order of the Legion of Honour]] on 14 May 1806.<ref name=\":0\" /> During the [[Battle of Jena\u2013Auerstedt|battle of Auerstedt]] (14 October 1806), captain Higonet showed skill and daring, but his brother, Colonel Joseph Higonet, died there (his name would later be [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|engraved]] [[Names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe|under the Arc de Triomphe]], Eastern pillar, column 18). He distinguished himself again on 8 February 1807 during the [[battle of Eylau]], where he was again wounded in the left leg and the lower abdomen. In 1809, he took part in the [[Battle of Eckm\u00fchl|battles of Eckm\u00fchl]] (21-22 April 1809) and [[Battle of Wagram|Wagram]] (5-6 July 1809). His heroic conduct was rewarded on 22 June 1809 by his assignment to the 1st Infantry Grenadier Regiment from the prestigious [[Imperial Guard (Napoleon I)|Imperial Guard]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\nIn 1812 he was still Captain of the Grenadiers of the Imperial Guard when he took part in the [[French invasion of Russia|campaign of Russia]]. He returned with a frozen foot and the rank of [[Major]] in second. During the campaign of Germany, he took part in the siege of [[Hamburg]] in September 1813. On 1st March 1814, just before the abdication of Emperor Napoleon I, Marshal Davout elevated him to the rank of [[Colonel]], considering him as \"''one of the most brilliant officers in the army''.\"<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\nDuring the first Restoration, king [[Louis XVIII of France]] awarded him the cross of Knight of the [[Order of Saint Louis]]. Shortly after, the Colonel received command of the troops of Aveyron. But when Napoleon returned from [[Elba]], Marshal Davout, Minister of War during the [[Hundred Days]], placed Colonel Higonet at the head of the 10th Line Infantry Regiment, then of his former 108th Line Infantry Regiment. He then distinguished himself at the [[battle of Quatre Bras]] (16 June 1815), where he was wounded twice and then at the [[battle of Waterloo]] (18 June 1815), during the debacle of the French army.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Under the Restoration ===\nAfter Napoleon's second abdication, Philippe Higonet rallied to [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis XVIII]], who appointed him to form and command the Legion of Cantal on 19 August 1815. On 8 June 1816, he married Augustine, daughter of Baron Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de Jujeals de Peyrac de Veillan. King Louis XVIII made him [[Baron]] shortly after. He then chose the motto of his coat of arms as \"''Virtus, labor, pietas''\".<ref name=\":22\" /> He was also made Officer of the [[Legion of Honour|Order of the Legion of Honour]] that same year of 1816.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe command of the 9th Line Infantry Regiment was then entrusted to Colonel Philippe Higonet, with whom he participated in 1823 in the [[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis|expedition of Spain]]. On 11 August 1823, he was promoted to [[Mar\u00e9chal de camp]] (Brigadier General) in recognition of his acts of bravery during the siege of [[Pamplona]]. During the siege of [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]] on 3 September 1823, he obtained the capitulation of the city on the 28. The campaign finished, he then returned to France in March 1823. The following year, on 8 June 1824, he was promoted Commander of the [[Legion of Honour|Order of the Legion of Honour]] and raised to the dignity of Grand Officer of the [[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand|Order of Saint Ferdinand of Spain]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n[[File:Entrevue_du_g\u00e9n\u00e9ral_Maison_et_d'Ibrahim_Pacha,_\u00e0_Navarin,_septembre_1828_(d\u00e9tail).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|220x220px|The French military expedition of Morea in 1828 (by Jean-Charles Langlois)]]\nBy the ordinance of 24 July 1828, he was then sent to Greece as a field marshal to participate in the [[Morea expedition|Morea expedition (1828)]], under the orders of [[Nicolas Joseph Maison|Marshal Maison]], during the [[Greek War of Independence]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> At the head of the 2nd brigade of the expeditionary forces, he liberated the city of [[Pylos|Navarino]] (on 7 October 1828) from the Turkish-Egyptian occupation troops of [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] and then took the \"Castle of Morea\" of [[Patras]] (on 30 October 1828).<ref name=\":172\">[[Nicolas-Joseph Maison]] (Lieutenant-g\u00e9n\u00e9ral) : ''d\u00e9p\u00eaches adress\u00e9es au ministre de la Guerre Louis-Victor de Caux, vicomte de Blacquetot,'' octobre 1828, in Jacques Mangeart, Chapitre Suppl\u00e9mentaire des ''[https://books.google.gr/books?id=OixCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Souvenirs de la Mor\u00e9e: recueillis pendant le s\u00e9jour des Fran\u00e7ais dans le Pelopon\u00e8se]'', Igonette, Paris, 1830.</ref> Higonet stayed for a few months in Patras and he established there several health commissions for the freed but suffering Greek population, and even managed, in December 1828, to contain an [[Plague (disease)|outbreak of plague]] which was developing in the mountainous villages of [[Kalavryta]] and Vrachni.<ref name=\":152\">Jacques Mangeart, ''[https://books.google.gr/books?id=OixCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Souvenirs de la Mor\u00e9e: recueillis pendant le s\u00e9jour des Fran\u00e7ais dans le Pelopon\u00e8se]'', Igonette; Paris, 1830.</ref> He finally left the Greek soil after four months of mission in the Peloponnese, on 9 January 1829, after having completely liberated Greece from the occupier.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":172\" /><ref>Site internet \"histoire-en-questions.fr\". Blessures d'un soldat de l'Empire</ref> During this campaign, on 22 February 1829, he was promoted by king [[Charles X of France|Charles X]] Commander of the [[Order of Saint Louis|Royal and Military Order of Saint-Louis]] and then, on his return to France, Commander of the [[Order of the Redeemer]] by the new independent Greek State, in 1830.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Parliamentary activities ===\nShortly before the Morea expedition, on 17 November 1827, as President of the electoral college of [[Cantal]], he had been elected deputy (favorable to [[Charles X of France|Charles X]]) of the 1st arrondissement of this department ([[Aurillac]]) at the [[Chamber of Deputies (France)|Chamber of Deputies]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> He was re-elected for a second term of deputy on 23 June 1830.<ref>List of the parliamentary terms and biography on the site of the French National Assembly: [http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/sycomore/fiche/(num_dept)/14695 ''Philippe Higonet (1782 - 1859)'']</ref>\n\nBut following the [[July Revolution]], he resigned from his deputy mandate on 12 August 1830, and chose exile from the inside. After the [[French Revolution of 1848]], he came out of his retirement and tried to be re-elected for a mandate of representative of the people at the [[National Assembly (France)|National Legislative Assembly]] of the [[French Second Republic|Second Republic]], but this time without success. <ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Last years ===\nAfter his resignation from his mandate as deputy on 12 August 1830, Philippe Higonet was placed on availability, retired to Aurillac and devoted himself, during eighteen years, to the administration of the domain of the Ch\u00e2teau de Veyrac, to which he made many improvements,<ref name=\":22\" /> and dealt exclusively with agriculture, becoming president of the Cantal Agriculture Society.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nOn 30 May 1848, he retired as a [[Mar\u00e9chal de camp]] (Brigadier General). \n\nHe supported the candidacy of [[Napoleon III|Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte]] during the presidential election of December 1848, but refused to swear allegiance after his coup of 2 December 1851. He then spent the last years of his life at Aurillac. Because of the wounds he received in February 1807 during the battle of Eylau, which made him suffer cruelly, he died on 12 February 1859 in [[Aurillac]], at the age of 77. He was buried in the town's Massigoux cemetery. On one side of the funerary stele, his name and his honorary distinctions are surrounded by a mandorla (oval almond) on which are inscribed the names of his main battles: [[Mariazell]], Austerlitz, Eylau, Les Quatre Bras, San Sebastian, Pamplona, Navarino and the Castle of Morea.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n== Decorations, military ranks and representative positions ==\n* [[File:French_heraldic_crowns_-_baron_et_pair.svg|60px]] 1st [[Baron|Baron Higonet]] (1816)\n* [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] of the district of Cantal (1827-1830)\n* [[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]] (''G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de brigade'') of the French army.\n* French decorations:\n** [[File:Ordre_Royal_et_Militaire_de_Saint-Louis_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Order of Saint Louis|''Commander'' of the Royal and Military Order of Saint-Louis]] (22 February 1829).\n** [[File:Legion_Honneur_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Knight'' of the Order of the Legion of Honour]] (14 May 1806).\n** [[File:Legion_Honneur_Officier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Officer'']] [[Legion of Honour|of the Legion of Honour]] (1816).\n** [[File:Legion_Honneur_Commandeur_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Commander'']] [[Legion of Honour|of the Legion of Honour]] (8 June 1824).\n* Foreign decorations:\n** [[File:ESP_Laureada_pasador.svg|60px]] [[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand|''Grand officer'' of the Order of Saint Ferdinand (Spain)]] (1823)\n** [[File:GRE_Order_Redeemer_3Class.png|60px]] [[Order of the Redeemer|''Commander'' of the Order of the Redeemer (Greece)]] (1830)\n\n== Annexes ==\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* \u00ab Le g\u00e9n\u00e9ral baron Higonet (Philippe)\u00bb , notice dans Aim\u00e9 de Birague, ''M\u00e9morial universel g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique et biographique'', Institut des archives historiques, Paris, 1851-1852.\n* {{DicoParlement}}.\n* Bernard Maury, \u00ab ''[http://www.genealogie-aveyron.fr/spip.php?article1295 G\u00e9n\u00e9ral Baron Philippe Higonet, Comment un Marmot est devenu G\u00e9n\u00e9ral et Baron]'' \u00bb, Cercle g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique de l\u2019Aveyron, \u00e9dit\u00e9 par Suzanne Barthe, 27 juillet 2018.\n\n=== External links ===\n* Resources related to his public life: [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/leonore_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=COTE&VALUE_1=LH/875/60 Base L\u00e9onore] ; [http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/sycomore/fiche.asp?num_dept=14443 Base Sycomore] : \n**{{Base L\u00e9onore|LH/1300/58}} (National Order of the Legion of Honour)\n**[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/sycomore/fiche/(num_dept)/14695 \u00ab List of the parliamentary terms of Philippe Higonet (1782 - 1859) \u00bb, Base Sycomore], [[National Assembly (France)|(French National Assembly)]].\n\n=== Linked articles ===\n* [[Morea expedition]]\n* [[List of members of the Morea expedition (1828-1833)]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Portal|histoire militaire|politique fran\u00e7aise|Cantal\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Higonet, Philippe}}\n\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Saint Louis]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of the Bourbon Restoration]]\n[[Category:People from Cantal]]\n[[Category:WikiProject Europe articles]]\n[[Category:WikiProject France articles]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1851-1852 \u2192 1851\u20131852", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippe_Higonet"}
{"title_page": "Fremont, Nebraska", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Fremont, Nebraska\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| motto                           = \n| image_skyline                   = Fremont, Nebraska 3rd and Main looking NW.JPG\n| alt                             = Street with one- and two-story buildings\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Fremont's historic downtown is listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = \n| image_map                       = Dodge_County_Nebraska_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Fremont_Highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Location in [[Nebraska]]\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of counties in Nebraska|County]]\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Nebraska]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Dodge County, Nebraska|Dodge]]\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Scott Getzschman<ref>[http://www.fremontne.gov/index.aspx?NID=29 \"City Council\".]  [http://www.fremontne.gov/index.aspx City of Fremont.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510020847/http://www.fremontne.gov/index.aspx |date=2012-05-10 }} Retrieved 2012-05-22.</ref>\n| area_magnitude                  = 1 E8\n| established_title               = Founded\n| established_title2              = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n| established_date                = June 17, 1871\n| established_date2               = 1873\n\n<!-- Area -->| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_31.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 12, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 27.14\n| area_land_km2                   = 26.98\n| area_water_km2                  = 0.16\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 10.48\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 10.42\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 0.06\n| area_urban_sq_mi                = \n| area_urban_km2                  = \n| area_metro_sq_mi                = \n| area_metro_km2                  = \n| population_footnotes            = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_est                  = 26509\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 26397\n| population_metro                = \n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_km2          = 980.70\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 2540.03\n| timezone                        = [[North American Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| utc_offset                      = &minus;6\n| timezone_DST                    = [[North American Central Time Zone|CDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = &minus;5\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|41|26|23|N|96|29|24|W|region:US-NE_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_m                     = 366\n| elevation_ft                    = 1203\n| postal_code_type                = ZIP codes\n| postal_code                     = 68025-68026\n| area_code                       = 402\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 31-17670\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = 0829408<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n| website                         = [http://www.fremontne.gov/ fremontne.gov]\n| footnotes                       = \n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| official_name                   = \n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \"F-Town\" \"The Mont\"\n}}\n\n'''Fremont''' is a city in [[Dodge County, Nebraska|Dodge County]] in the eastern portion of the state of [[Nebraska]] in the [[Midwestern United States]].  The population was 26,397 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].  Fremont is the county seat and the home of [[Midland University]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:John Charles Fr\u00e9mont.png|thumb|right|[[John C. Fremont]] is the city's namesake.]]\nFrom the 1830s to the 1860s, the area saw a great deal of traffic due to the [[Mormon Trail]], which passed along the north bank of the [[Platte River]]. A ferry connected the two banks of the [[Elkhorn River]] near Fremont. It was a major overland route for emigrant [[settlers]] going to the West, the military and hunters.\n\nFremont was laid out in 1856 in anticipation that the railroad would be extended to that site.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.casde.unl.edu/history/counties/dodge/fremont/ | title=Fremont, Dodge County | publisher=University of Nebraska | work=Center for Advanced Land Management Information Technologies | accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> It was named after the American explorer, politician and military official General [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/genInfo.php?locIndex=27383 | title=Profile for Fremont, NE | publisher=[[ePodunk]] | accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Chicago and North Western Railway Company|title=A History of the Origin of the Place Names Connected with the Chicago & North Western and Chicago, St. Paul, Minneapolis & Omaha Railways|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OspBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA74|year=1908|page=74}}</ref>  By 1857, there were 13 log houses in the town. The [[Union Pacific Railroad]] reached the town in 1866 becoming the first railroad into the future rail hub.  [[Sioux City and Pacific Railroad]] completed track into the town in 1868 with the [[Fremont, Elkhorn and Missouri Valley Railroad|Elkhorn Valley Railroad]] arriving in 1869.<ref name=bowman>{{cite book|last1=Bowman|first1=J. R.|editor1-last=Shearer|editor1-first=Frederick E.|title=The Pacific tourist. J.R. Bowman's illustrated transcontinental guide of travel from the Atlantic to the Pacific Ocean|date=1882|publisher=J.R. Bowman|location=New York|page=23|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nbsUAAAAYAAJ&dq=The%20Pacific%20tourist.%20J.R.%20Bowman's%20illustrated%20transcontinental%20guide%20of%20travel%20from%20the%20Atlantic%20to%20the%20Pacific%20Ocean&pg=PA23#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=9 May 2018|oclc=752667534}}</ref>\n\nDue to the town's geographically central location, the [[First Transcontinental Telegraph]] line (1861), [[First Transcontinental Railroad (North America)|railroad]] (1866) and highway (1913) passed through or very near Fremont. Original brick portions of the \"[[Lincoln Highway|Old Lincoln Highway]]\" are located east of Fremont, on the way to [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]].\n\nFremont is the namesake for the [[Fremont, Seattle|Fremont]] neighborhood in Seattle, which was settled by Luther H. Griffith and Edward Blewett from Fremont.<ref>Helen Divjak, ''Seattle's Fremont'', Arcadia Publishing (2006, Images of America series), {{ISBN|978-0-7385-3119-9}}. p. 9.</ref>\n\nOn January 10, 1976, in downtown Fremont, the Pathfinder Hotel exploded due to a [[natural gas]] leak in the basement. At the time the hotel was being used as apartments, mostly occupied by senior citizens. It also was a meeting place for philanthropic and business organizations, and had a drug store on the northwest corner. The [[explosion]] shattered windows around the city, and the ensuing fire killed 23 people and destroyed most of the city block of the hotel.\n\nFremont gained national attention in 2010 when residents approved a referendum that would ban [[illegal immigration|illegal immigrants]] from renting and working in the town.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davey|first=Monica|title=Nebraska Town Votes to Banish Illegal Immigrants|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/22/us/22fremont.html|accessdate=2010-06-22|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2010-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dwyer Arce|url=http://jurist.org/paperchase/2010/06/nebraska-city-voters-pass-ban-on-hiring-renting-to-illegal-immigrants.php|title=Nebraska city voters pass ban on hiring, renting to illegal immigrants|date=2010-06-22|publisher=JURIST - Paper Chase}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nFremont is located along the [[Platte River]], approximately {{convert|35|mi|km}} northwest of the largest city in the area, [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]], and {{convert|50|mi|km}} northeast of the state capitol, [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|8.85|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which, {{convert|8.80|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.05|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-06-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref> Fremont is quite flat, lying in the river plain between the Platte and Elkhorn rivers, at an elevation of approximately 366 meters (1,203&nbsp;ft) above sea level.\n\n===Climate===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \"text-align:cente