e 8, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nFremont is the county seat of [[Dodge County, Nebraska|Dodge County]], [[Nebraska]], and is likewise the financial and social center of the area. Facilitated by the completion of the US Highway 275 and Highway 30 [[Bypass route|bypass]] around Fremont, from [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]], eastern Fremont is growing rapidly as a [[bedroom community]] for Omaha (see links to air photos below).\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234628/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-06-24}}</ref> of 2010, there were 26,397 people, 10,725 households, and 6,862 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|2999.7|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 11,427 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1298.5|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 89.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.7% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.6% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.6% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.3% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 7.1% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.6% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 11.9% of the population.\n\nThere were 10,725 households of which 31.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 11.2% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.9% had a male householder with no wife present, and 36.0% were non-families. 30.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.38 and the average family size was 2.94.\n\nThe median age in the city was 38 years. 24.2% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 23.9% were from 25 to 44; 24.7% were from 45 to 64; and 17.3% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 48.5% male and 51.5% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, there were 25,174 people, 10,171 households, and 6,672 families living in the city, which makes it the 6th largest city in Nebraska. The [[population density]] was 3,393.3 people per square mile (1,309.9/km\u00b2). There were 10,576 housing units at an average density of 1,425.6 per square mile (550.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 95.28% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.57% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.31% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.61% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.11% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 2.29% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.82% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 4.31% of the population.\n\nThere were 10,171 households out of which 30.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 9.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.4% were non-families. 29.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.38 and the average family size was 2.93.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 24.2% under the age of 18, 11.0% from 18 to 24, 26.7% from 25 to 44, 20.7% from 45 to 64, and 17.4% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females, there were 90.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $36,700, and the median income for a family was $45,259. Males had a median income of $31,865 versus $21,035 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $18,006. About 5.1% of families and 8.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 10.1% of those under age 18 and 7.2% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\nAs of 2016, Fremont's single largest employer was [[Hormel|Hormel Foods]], with an estimated 1000\u20131500 workers,<ref name=\":0\" /> whose hog-processing plant has been described as \"the nation\u2019s largest producer of [[Spam (food)|Spam]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://slate.com/business/2017/12/latino-immigrants-and-meatpacking-in-midwestern-towns-like-fremont-nebraska.html|title=Immigrants Could Save the Only Town in America That Passed a Law to Keep Them Out|last=Grabar|first=Henry|date=December 6, 2017|work=Slate Magazine|access-date=2017-12-12|language=en}}</ref>  The next-largest employers were Fremont Health Medical Center, Fremont Public Schools, and Nye Health Services, each with an estimated 500\u20131000 employees.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fremontecodev.org/media/userfiles/subsite_34/files/resources/MAJOR_EMPLOYERS_2016.pdf |title=Fremont Area Major Employers |publisher=Greater Fremont Development Council |access-date=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Costco]] began building a poultry complex in 2019 that includes a processing facility, hatchery and feed mill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/11/business/costco-5-dollar-chicken/index.html|title=It's only $4.99. But Costco's rotisserie chicken comes at a huge price|last=Meyersohn|first=Nathaniel|date=October 11, 2019|website=CNN|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and culture==\nThe Louis E. May Historical Museum is housed in a [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] house built by Fremont's first mayor, Theron Nye, in 1874. A log cabin on the site is an example of the type of dwelling in which the earliest pioneers lived who moved to Nebraska as part of the [[Homestead Act]]. Historic downtown Fremont is known for its numerous antique stores, and a collection of historical buildings.\n\n[[File:Dodge County, Nebraska courthouse from NE 1.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Dodge County Courthouse in Fremont, Nebraska]]\n\nSeveral local buildings are on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP). Among these is the Love-Larson Opera House on Broad Street, built in 1888. Later used as apartments and a grocery store, it was restored for theatre use by a non-profit group in the 1970s, and again in 2003 by the Fremont High Drama Club.\n\n[[John C. Fremont]] Days, which is a celebration of Fremont's history through a parade, [[Chautauqua]], [[rodeo]], classic car show and vendors with handmade crafts.\n\nThe Fremont Lakes State Recreation Area (also known as \"the State Lakes\") attracts boaters, skiers, fishermen and beachgoers from the area to the group of 20 man-made tree-lined lakes which cover nearly {{convert|700|acre|km2}}, along the [[Platte River]]. Two regional [[Scouting in Nebraska|Boy Scout]] camps, Camp Cedars and Camp Eagle, are located near Fremont, along the Platte River.\n\nFremont forms part of the [[Nebraska Statewide Arboretum]] collection.\n\n==Parks and recreation==\nFremont has 21 city-owned parks, with a combined area of over {{convert|400|acre|km2}}. Located in the northwest corner of Fremont near the \"Washington Heights\" neighborhood is the Fremont Golf Club (FGC). The FGC was completed in 1930 and features {{convert|6390|yd}} of golf from the longest tees for a par of 71.\n\nIn 2007 construction of the \"Splash Station\" water park was completed. The park cost an estimated $5.1&nbsp;million and features an interactive train slide, combination lap pool and wave pool, body slide and speed slide.\n\n==Education==\nFremont is the home of the undergraduate [[liberal arts college]], [[Midland University]], which houses the Musbach Art Center, among other attractions. The [[Metropolitan Community College (Omaha)|Metropolitan Community College]] system has a [[community college]] campus in Fremont as well.\n\nThere is one public [[High school (North America)|high school]], [[Fremont Senior High School (Nebraska)|Fremont Senior High]] (part of the Fremont Public School System), one private school, [[Archbishop Bergan High School|Archbishop Bergan Catholic School]] (Pre-K-12), and one private elementary/middle school, Trinity Lutheran School.\n\n==Transportation==\n* [[U.S. Route 30]]\n* [[U.S. Route 77]]\n* [[U.S. Route 275]]\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[William L. Armstrong]], served as a United States [[United States Representative|Representative]] and [[United States Senator|Senator]] from [[Colorado]]<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=A000219|title=ARMSTRONG, William Lester, (1937 - )|dictionary=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Mildred Banfield]], Alaska state legislator<ref>'Former State Legislator Banfield Dies in Arizona,' '''Sikta Daily Sentinel,''' June 7, 1991, pg. 7</ref> \n* [[Sue Bierman]], San Francisco civic activist and [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors|Supervisor]]<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=http://fremonttribune.com/news/local/obituaries/susan-bierman/article_893e8aaf-91bb-58c2-906d-96a95fcc6f06.html|title=Susan Bierman|last=|first=|date=August 10, 2006|work=|newspaper=Fremont Tribune|access-date=2016-12-31|via=}}</ref>\n* [[Gutzon Borglum]], sculptor<ref>Smith RA. (1985). The carving of Mount Rushmore. New York: Abbeville Press Publishers</ref>\n* [[Harold Eugene Edgerton]], pioneer in [[Stroboscope|stroboscopic]] photography<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usgennet.org/usa/ne/topic/resources/OLLibrary/Nebraskana/pages/nbka0099.htm|title=Harold Eugene Edgerton|publisher=Nebraska Genealogy|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Marg Helgenberger]], film and television actress<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001339/|title=Marg Helgenberger|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Charlie Janssen]], Nebraska State Auditor, former member of Nebraska legislature<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.org/bio/id/63139|title=Sen. Charlie Janssen (R-Nebraska) biography|publisher=Congress.org|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Doron Jensen]],{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} founder of [[Timber Lodge Steakhouse]]\n*[[James Milliken (college president)|James Milliken]], Chancellor of the [[University of Texas System]]\n*[[Richard A. Jensen]],{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} theologian and professor at [[Lutheran School of Theology at Chicago]]\n* [[Jason Licht]],{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} general manager of NFL's [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n* [[Ben Sasse]], United States [[United States Senator|Senator]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/367966/obamacares-nebraska-nemesis-nro-staff|title=\u2018Obamacare\u2019s Nebraska Nemesis\u2019|last=|first=|date=January 9, 2014|work=National Review|access-date=2017-12-12|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Julie Sommars]], film and television actress<ref name=mtc>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/julie-sommars|title=Julie Sommars|work=Metacritic|accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Sloppy Thurston]], [[starting pitcher]] in [[Major League Baseball]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/t/thurssl01.shtml|title=Sloppy Thurston|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Zach Wiegert]], player in the [[National Football League]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/W/WiegZa20.htm|title=Zach Wiegert|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://fremontne.gov City of Fremont]\n*[https://visitfremontne.org/ Fremont & Dodge County Convention & Visitor Bureau]\n* [http://www.fremontne.org/ Fremont Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://www.fremontneb.com/ The Fremont Tribune]\n* [http://www.mainstreetfremont.org/ Main Street Fremont]\n\n{{Dodge County, Nebraska}}\n{{Nebraska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Micropolitan areas of Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Dodge County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Fremont, Nebraska| ]]\n[[Category:County seats in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1871]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Nebraska]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Fremont, Nebraska\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| motto                           = \n| image_skyline                   = Fremont, Nebraska 3rd and Main looking NW.JPG\n| alt                             = Street with one- and two-story buildings\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = Fremont's historic downtown is listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = \n| image_map                       = Dodge_County_Nebraska_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Fremont_Highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Location in [[Nebraska]]\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of counties in Nebraska|County]]\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Nebraska]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Dodge County, Nebraska|Dodge]]\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Scott Getzschman<ref>[http://www.fremontne.gov/index.aspx?NID=29 \"City Council\".]  [http://www.fremontne.gov/index.aspx City of Fremont.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive